<h2>WHOIS: The Internet's Oldest Public Database</h2>
<p>Every domain name on the internet has an owner — an individual, a company, or an organization that registered it through an accredited registrar. WHOIS is the protocol and database that stores this information. Since the earliest days of the internet (RFC 812, published in 1982), WHOIS has served as the public record of domain ownership. Want to know when a domain was registered? WHOIS tells you. When does it expire? WHOIS tells you. Which registrar manages it? Which name servers does it use? All public, all queryable, all through a protocol older than the web itself.</p>
<p>A <a href="/tools/whois-lookup/">WHOIS lookup tool</a> queries distributed WHOIS servers — each TLD (.com, .org, .io, .dev) has its own registry and WHOIS server — and returns the data in a (mostly) human-readable format. The exact information available depends on the TLD and whether the registrant has enabled privacy protection. But even with privacy enabled, key dates and technical details remain public. That's by design: the internet's naming system needs transparency to function.</p>

<h2>What WHOIS Tells You (and What It Doesn't)</h2>
<p><strong>Creation Date.</strong> When the domain was first registered. This is one of the most useful pieces of information in WHOIS. A domain registered yesterday and sending phishing emails is a clear threat. A domain registered in 1998 that's been continuously renewed is more likely legitimate. Creation dates are also tracked by domain investors — a domain that was registered 15 years ago and never dropped has "aged" and may have accumulated SEO value (backlinks, domain authority) independently of its current content.</p>
<p><strong>Expiration Date.</strong> When the domain registration expires if not renewed. Domains don't disappear the moment they expire — there's a grace period (typically 30-45 days) during which the original registrant can renew without penalty, followed by a redemption period where renewal is possible but expensive ($80-200), and finally a pending delete phase before the domain returns to the public pool. WHOIS shows the exact expiration date, which tells you how long until the domain could potentially become available.</p>
<p><strong>Registrar.</strong> The company where the domain was registered — GoDaddy, Namecheap, Google Domains, Cloudflare Registrar. This is useful for competitive research (where does this company buy its domains?) and for understanding renewal and transfer options if you're looking to acquire the domain.</p>
<p><strong>Name Servers.</strong> The DNS servers authoritative for the domain. These tell you where the domain's DNS is hosted — Cloudflare, AWS Route 53, DNS Made Easy, or the registrar's default DNS. Combined with other tools like our <a href="/tools/dns-lookup/">DNS Lookup</a>, name server information helps you understand a site's full infrastructure stack.</p>
<p><strong>Registrant Contact.</strong> This is where things get complicated. Pre-2018, WHOIS typically showed the registrant's name, organization, email address, phone number, and physical address. Post-GDPR (May 2018), most registrars redact this information or offer WHOIS privacy protection by default. If a domain has privacy protection enabled, you'll see the registrar's proxy contact information instead of the actual owner's details. This is normal and expected — it's not a sign that the domain owner is hiding anything. The EU's GDPR made privacy the default for individuals, and most registrars extended this globally.</p>

<h2>When to Use WHOIS</h2>
<p><strong>Security investigations.</strong> A phishing email links to a domain that looks like your bank but isn't. WHOIS shows the domain was registered three days ago through a registrar in a different country. That combination — recent registration, foreign registrar, brand-impersonating domain — is the signature of a phishing campaign. Forward the WHOIS data to your security team and the domain's registrar's abuse contact.</p>
<p><strong>Domain acquisition.</strong> You want to buy a domain that's already registered. WHOIS tells you when it expires and which registrar manages it. If the registrant's contact information is public, you can reach out directly. If it's private, you can go through the registrar's domain buy service or use a domain broker. Knowing the expiration date also tells you whether it's worth waiting for the domain to expire or pursuing acquisition now.</p>
<p><strong>Competitive research.</strong> A competitor's site uses a specific registrar and DNS provider. Combined with our <a href="/tools/dns-lookup/">DNS Lookup tool</a>, you can map out their infrastructure choices — which CDN they use, where their email is hosted (MX records), and whether they use any security services. This isn't spying; it's all public information that any DNS or WHOIS query returns.</p>
<p><strong>Brand protection.</strong> Monitor WHOIS for domains containing your trademark. Registrars are required to provide WHOIS access, and services exist that automate this monitoring. If someone registers "yourbrand-shop.com" and points it at a phishing site, catching it early via WHOIS monitoring limits the damage. Most large brands use domain monitoring services, but a manual WHOIS lookup is the first step in investigating any suspicious domain.</p>

<h2>Limitations of WHOIS</h2>
<p>WHOIS data is not always accurate. Registrants can provide false information (though this violates ICANN policy and can result in domain suspension). Privacy protection hides contact details. Different TLDs have different WHOIS formats and availability — some ccTLDs (country-code TLDs like .de, .co.uk, .cn) have their own WHOIS systems with different fields and restrictions. And WHOIS rate limiting means you can't query hundreds of domains in rapid succession from the same IP address. For bulk domain research, use the registrar's API or a paid WHOIS database service rather than hammering public WHOIS servers.</p>
<p>Also, note that RDAP (Registration Data Access Protocol) is gradually replacing WHOIS. RDAP returns structured JSON instead of free-form text, making it easier to parse programmatically. Our <a href="/tools/whois-lookup/">WHOIS lookup</a> attempts RDAP first and falls back to traditional WHOIS when RDAP isn't available for a given TLD.</p>
